As well as anchoring the cilium, it is thought to provide a selective gateway regulating the entry of ciliary proteins and vesicles by intraflagellar transport.
A ciliary basal body that is part of a kinocilium.
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a left anterior flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a right anterior flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a left posteriolateral flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a right posteriolateral flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a left ventral flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a right ventral flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a left caudal flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).
Any ciliary basal body that is part of a right caudal flagellum found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage).

StringWithMarkup.String: intermediate layer of spindle pole body

nodes.description: Structure between the central and outer plaques of the spindle pole body.

StringWithMarkup.String: intermediate layer of mitotic spindle pole body

nodes.description: Structure between the central and outer plaques of the mitotic spindle pole body.

StringWithMarkup.String: inner plaque of spindle pole body

nodes.description: One of three laminate structures that form the spindle pole body; the inner plaque is in the nucleus.

StringWithMarkup.String: inner plaque of mitotic spindle pole body

nodes.description: One of three laminate structures that form the mitotic spindle pole body; the inner plaque is in the nucleus.

StringWithMarkup.String: central plaque of spindle pole body

nodes.description: One of three laminate structures that form the spindle pole body; the central plaque is embedded in the nuclear envelope.

StringWithMarkup.String: central plaque of mitotic spindle pole body

nodes.description: One of three laminate structures that form the mitotic spindle pole body; the inner plaque is on the nuclear face of the spindle pole body.

StringWithMarkup.String: outer plaque of spindle pole body

nodes.description: One of three laminate structures that form the spindle pole body; the outer plaque is in the cytoplasm.

StringWithMarkup.String: outer plaque of mitotic spindle pole body

nodes.description: One of three laminate structures that form the mitotic spindle pole body; the outer plaque is in the cytoplasm.

StringWithMarkup.String: half bridge of spindle pole body

nodes.description: Structure adjacent to the plaques of the spindle pole body.

StringWithMarkup.String: half bridge of mitotic spindle pole body

nodes.description: Structure adjacent to the plaques of the mitotic spindle pole body.
The part of the cytoplasm that does not contain organelles but which does contain other particulate matter, such as protein complexes.
Any (proper) part of the cytosol of a single cell of sufficient size to still be considered cytosol.
The region of the cytosol consisting of all cytosol that is part of the presynapse.
The region of the cytosol consisting of all cytosol that is part of the postsynapse.
The bundle of microtubules and associated proteins that forms the core of cilia (also called flagella) in eukaryotic cells and is responsible for their movements.

A protuberance from a cell of an organism that reproduces by budding, which will grow larger and become a separate daughter cell after nuclear division, cytokinesis, and cell wall formation (when appropriate). The daughter cell may completely separate from the mother cell, or the mother and daughter cells may remain associated.
The region of a virus, bacterial cell, mitochondrion or chloroplast to which the nucleic acid is confined.
The region of a mitochondrion to which the DNA is confined.
The region of a plastid to which the DNA is confined.
The region of a chloroplast to which the DNA is confined.
The region of a proplastid to which the DNA is confined.
The region of a bacterial cell to which the DNA is confined.
The long, slender, mid section of a pilus.
The pointed extremity furthest from the cell of a pilus.
The long (approximately 20 nm), thin external structure of the bacterial-type flagellum, which acts as a propeller.
The proteinaceous structure at the distal tip of the bacterial-type flagellar filament.
The region of the bacterial-type flagellum where the hook and filament meet.
The portion of the bacterial-type flagellum that connects the filament to the basal body.

One of the three major substructures of the bacterial-type flagellum, the basal body is embedded in the cell envelope (the plasma membrane, peptidoglycan cell wall, and, if one is present, the outer membrane); it houses the secretion apparatus that exports the more distal components and the flagellar motor.

StringWithMarkup.String: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, distal rod

nodes.description: The portion of the central rod of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body that is distal to the cell membrane; spans most of the distance between the inner and outer membranes.

StringWithMarkup.String: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, distal rod, L ring

nodes.description: One of the rings of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body; anchors the basal body to the outer membrane.

StringWithMarkup.String: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, distal rod, P ring

nodes.description: One of the rings of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body; anchors the basal body to the peptidoglycan layer.

StringWithMarkup.String: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, proximal rod

nodes.description: The portion of the central rod of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body that is proximal to the cell membrane; the proximal rod connects the distal rod to the flagellar motor.

StringWithMarkup.String: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, MS ring

nodes.description: One of the rings of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body; a double-flanged ring that anchors the basal body to the cytoplasmic membrane.

StringWithMarkup.String: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, C ring

nodes.description: Cytoplasmic ring located at the base of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body; acts as a rotor; includes three switch proteins, which generate torque and can change their conformational state in a bimodal fashion, so that the motor direction can switch between clockwise and counterclockwise.

The nascent cell membrane and cell wall structure that forms between two daughter nuclei near the center of a dividing plant cell. It develops at the equatorial region of the phragmoplast. It grows outwards to join with the lateral walls and form two daughter cells.

A tightly wound cylinder of membrane that is located within the plasmodesmal pore and runs the length of the plasmodesma. The desmotubule likely provides a rigid stability to plasmodesmata and confers a fixed diameter and pore size to the plasmodesmal canal, and is linked to the endoplasmic reticulum in each of the adjacent cell.

The phragmoplast is a plant cell specific cytoplasmic structure composed of cytoskeletal polymers, membranes, and associated cytosolic proteins that functions as the focused secretory module for assembling the cell plate.
A flattened membranous vesicle containing cell wall components.
The proteinaceous ground substance of plastids.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of a chloroplast but excluding the thylakoid space. It contains DNA, ribosomes and some temporary products of photosynthesis.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of a proplastid.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of a chromoplast but excluding the photosynthetic material.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of a leucoplast.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of an elaioplast.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of an etioplast but excluding the prothylakoid space. It contains the etioplast DNA.
The space enclosed by the double membrane of a cyanelle.
Any plastid stroma that is part of a gerontoplast.

A three dimensional regular lattice found in etioplasts. It is composed of a continuous system of tubules but when exposed to light the symmetrical arrangement is rapidly lost as tubules become pinched off into two dimensional sections of lattice. These for perforated sheets of membrane that move apart, extend and increase, finally establishing the typical granal and intergranal lamellae of the mature chloroplast.
Distinct stack of lamellae seen within chloroplasts. Grana contain the pigments, electron transfer compounds, and enzymes essential to the light-dependent reactions of photosynthesis.
The space between the plasma membrane and the desmotubule of a plasmodesma.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a plasmodesma.

A microfibril composed of cellulose arranged in orthogonal layers. Cellulose is a straight chain polysaccharide composed of B(14) linked glucose subunits. It is a major component of plant cell walls. Higher plant microfibrils are about 10nm in diameter and extremely long in relation to their width. The cellulose molecules are oriented parallel to the long axis of the microfibril in a paracrystalline array, which provides great tensile strength. The microfibrils are held in place by the wall matrix and their orientation is closely controlled by the cell.

A dense band of microtubules, 1-3 pm wide, that appears just beneath the cell membrane before the start of cell division in the cells of higher plants. It precedes the onset of prophase and then disappears as mitosis begins, yet it somehow determines the plane of orientation of the new cell plate forming in late telophase and marks the zone of the parental cell wall where fusion with the growing cell plate ultimately occurs.
The side of the cell parallel to the zygotic axis.
The external part of the cell wall and/or plasma membrane.

A lipoprotein particle present in chloroplasts. They are rich in non-polar lipids (triglycerides, esters) as well as in prenylquinones, plastoquinone and tocopherols. Plastoglobules are often associated with thylakoid membranes, suggesting an exchange of lipids with thylakoids.

Thin filamentous structure extending from the surface of all plastid types examined so far, including chloroplast, proplastid, etioplast, leucoplast, amyloplast, and chromoplast. In general, stromules are more abundant in tissues containing non-green plastids, and in cells containing smaller plastids. The primary function of stromules is still unresolved, although the presence of stromules markedly increases the plastid surface area, potentially increasing transport to and from the cytosol. Other functions of stromules, such as transfer of macromolecules between plastids and starch granule formation in cereal endosperm, may be restricted to particular tissues and cell types.
The side of the cell wall that is opposite to the side that faces the cell and its contents.

StringWithMarkup.String: external side of fungal-type cell wall

nodes.description: The side of the fungal-type cell wall that is opposite to the side that faces the cell and its contents.

A collection of membranous structures involved in transport within the cell. The main components of the endomembrane system are endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi bodies, vesicles, cell membrane and nuclear envelope. Members of the endomembrane system pass materials through each other or though the use of vesicles.
A region of the A band in which myosin-binding protein C is located and that can be seen by electron microscopy. This is a functional zone that also includes myosin.
The portion of the free sarcoplasmic reticulum consisting of longitudinal tubules that connect terminal cisternae.
A lipid bilayer along with all the proteins and protein complexes embedded in it and attached to it.

The prospore membrane is a double-membraned structure that extends from the cytoplasmic face of the spindle pole bodies to encompass the spindle pole bodies and the four nuclear lobes that are formed during meiosis. It helps isolate the meiotic nuclei from the cytoplasm during spore formation and serves as a foundation for the formation of the spore walls. An example of this component is found in Schizosaccharomyces pombe.

Stacks of endoplasmic reticulum (ER) membranes containing a high density of nuclear pores, thought to form from excess nuclear membrane components, that have been described in a number of different cells. Annulate lamellar membranes are continuous with and embedded within the ER.
The membrane surrounding a cell that separates the cell from its external environment. It consists of a phospholipid bilayer and associated proteins.
A type of plasma membrane that has been modified through addition of distinct intracellular and extracellular components, including ceramide, found in cornifying epithelial cells (corneocytes).

The outer membrane of a muscle cell, consisting of the plasma membrane, a covering basement membrane (about 100 nm thick and sometimes common to more than one fiber), and the associated loose network of collagen fibers.
A plasma membrane that is part of a sperm cell.

A scallop-shaped plaque, also referred to as an asymmetric unit membrane (AUM), found in the apical plasma membrane of urothelial superficial (umbrella) cells which form a a barrier to the passage of water and soluble toxic compounds found in urine. The plaques are thickened regions of membrane composed of uroplakin transmembrane proteins which form a crystalline array.

A part of the endomembrane system in the form of an invagination of a membrane upon which a clathrin coat forms, and that can be converted by vesicle budding into a clathrin-coated vesicle. Coated pits form on the plasma membrane, where they are involved in receptor-mediated selective transport of many proteins and other macromolecules across the cell membrane, in the trans-Golgi network, and on some endosomes.
The external membrane of Gram-negative bacteria or certain organelles such as mitochondria and chloroplasts; freely permeable to most ions and metabolites.
A lipid bilayer that forms the outermost membrane of the cell envelope; enriched in polysaccharide and protein; the outer leaflet of the membrane contains specific lipopolysaccharide structures.

A mycolic acid-rich cell outer membrane containing a lipid bilayer and long-chain mycolic acids (hydroxylated branched-chain fatty acids) that are covalently linked to the cell wall peptidoglycan via an arabinogalactan network. Found in mycobacteria and related genera (e.g. corynebacteria).
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing in a cellular organelle, lipid bilayer of an organelle envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the plastid envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope.
The pigmented membrane of a chloroplast thylakoid. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The outer membrane around a bacterial endospore, located between the endospore cortex and endospore coat.
A membrane that is one of the two lipid bilayers of an organelle envelope or the outermost membrane of single membrane bound organelle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the endoplasmic reticulum.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the smooth endoplasmic reticulum.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the sarcoplasmic reticulum.

The part of the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane that contains calcium release channels, is devoted to calcium release and is juxtaposed to transverse tubule membrane. The junctional sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane consists of the junctional region of the terminal cisterna membrane.

The part of the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane that contains calcium pumps and is devoted to calcium uptake. The free sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane consists of the longitudinal sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane and the non-junctional region of the terminal cisterna membrane.
The membrane of the endoplasmic reticulum tubular network.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the cortical endoplasmic reticulum.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any membrane-bounded vesicle in the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a cytoplasmic vesicle.

The acrosomal membrane region that underlies the acrosomal vesicle and is located toward the sperm nucleus. This region is responsible for molecular interactions allowing the sperm to penetrate the zona pellucida and fuses with the egg plasma membrane.
The acrosomal membrane region that underlies the plasma membrane of the sperm. This membrane fuses with the sperm plasma membrane as part of the acrosome reaction.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a late endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a multivesicular body.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endolysosome. An endolysosome is a transient hybrid organelle formed by fusion of a late endosome with a lysosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a recycling endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic recycling endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a presynaptic endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a macropinosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a transport vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: ER to Golgi transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi.

StringWithMarkup.String: Golgi to ER transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the Golgi to the ER.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances within the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances between the trans-Golgi network and other parts of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted acetylcholine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted glutamate transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted monoamine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an exocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a synaptic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle associated with the Golgi apparatus.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances between the trans-Golgi network and other parts of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a COPI-coated vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: Golgi to ER transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the Golgi to the ER.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances within the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a chitosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a coated vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: ER to Golgi transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a COPI-coated vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: Golgi to ER transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the Golgi to the ER.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances within the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances between the trans-Golgi network and other parts of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted acetylcholine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted glutamate transport vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: clathrin-sculpted gamma-aminobutyric acid transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted gamma-aminobutyric acid transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted monoamine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an early phagosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a phagolysosome.
A membrane that surrounds one or more bacteroids (such as nitrogen-fixing bacteroids within legume root nodule cells).
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, of the two lipid bilayers surrounding an organellar chromatophore.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a secretory granule.

The membrane that surrounds the acrosomal lumen. The acrosome is a special type of lysosome in the head of a spermatozoon that contains acid hydrolases and is concerned with the breakdown of the outer membrane of the ovum during fertilization.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the platelet dense granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the platelet alpha granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a dense core granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a neuronal dense core vesicle.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an azurophil granule, a primary lysosomal granule found in neutrophil granulocytes that contains a wide range of hydrolytic enzymes and is released into the extracellular fluid.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a specific granule, a granule with a membranous, tubular internal structure, found primarily in mature neutrophil cells. Most are released into the extracellular fluid. Specific granules contain lactoferrin, lysozyme, vitamin B12 binding protein and elastase.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a chromaffin granule, a specialized secretory vesicle found in the cells of adrenal glands and various other organs, which is concerned with the synthesis, storage, metabolism, and secretion of epinephrine and norepinephrine.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a zymogen granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a tertiary granule.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a lamellar body. A lamellar body is a membrane-bounded organelle, specialized for the storage and secretion of various substances (surfactant phospholipids, glycoproteins and acid phosphates) which are arranged in the form of tightly packed, concentric, membrane sheets or lamellae. Has some similar properties to, but is distinct from, a lysosome.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an alveolar lamellar body, a specialized secretory organelle found in type II pneumocytes and involved in the synthesis, secretion, and reutilization of pulmonary surfactant.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an epidermal lamellar body, a specialized secretory organelle found in keratinocytes and involved in the formation of an impermeable, lipid-containing membrane that serves as a water barrier and is required for correct skin barrier function.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a ficolin-1-rich granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a dense granule of the type found in apicomplexan parasites.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the contractile vacuole.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an aleurone grain.
Either of the two lipid bilayers surrounding a Cvt vesicle, a vesicle that functions in the cytoplasm-to-vacuole targeting (Cvt) pathway.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an esterosome. This membrane has characteristics of rough endoplasmic reticulum (RER) membranes.
The membrane of a gut granule, a lysosome-related organelle contained within the intestinal cells of the nematode C. elegans.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround an organellar chromatophore.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, of the two lipid bilayers surrounding an organellar chromatophore.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, of the two lipid bilayers surrounding an organellar chromatophore.
The lipid bilayer membrane of any thylakoid within an organellar chromatophore.
Any membrane that is part of a pigment granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a melanosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a multivesicular body internal vesicle.
The lipid bylayer surrounding a phagolysosome.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a rod photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of rhodopsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. It is thought that rod disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane near the base of the outer segment, which then become completely separated from the ciliary membrane, during the development of the rod outer segment.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of an organelle envelope; usually highly selective to most ions and metabolites.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the nuclear envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope. It is highly folded to form cristae.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the plastid envelope; also faces the plastid stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope; also faces the chloroplast stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope; also faces the chromoplast stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the amyloplast envelope; also faces the amyloplast stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope; also faces the cyanelle stroma.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the nucleus and form the nuclear envelope; excludes the intermembrane space.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the nuclear envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the mitochondrion and form the mitochondrial envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope. It is highly folded to form cristae.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the thin, flattened compartments that form the central portion of the Golgi complex.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the thin, flattened compartments that form the cis portion of the Golgi complex.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the thin, flattened compartments that form the medial portion of the Golgi complex.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the thin, flattened compartments that form the trans portion of the Golgi complex.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments that make up the trans-Golgi network.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a rhoptry.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround a plastid and form the plastid envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the plastid envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the plastid envelope; also faces the plastid stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope; also faces the chloroplast stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope; also faces the chromoplast stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the amyloplast envelope; also faces the amyloplast stroma.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope; also faces the cyanelle stroma.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround a chloroplast and form the chloroplast envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope; also faces the chloroplast stroma.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround an amyloplast and form the amyloplast envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the amyloplast envelope; also faces the amyloplast stroma.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround a cyanelle and form the cyanelle envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope; also faces the cyanelle stroma.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround a etioplast and form the etioplast envelope.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround a chromoplast and form the chromoplast envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope; also faces the chromoplast stroma.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope.
The lipid bilayer membrane of any thylakoid within a plastid.
The pigmented membrane of a chloroplast thylakoid. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The lipid bilayer membrane of any thylakoid within a cyanelle.
The membrane of prothylakoids, underdeveloped thylakoids found in etioplasts, lacking competent photosynthetic membranes.
Any of the lipid bilayers that surround an apicoplast and form the apicoplast envelope.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. Disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane during the development of the outer segment and may or may not remain contiguous with the ciliary membrane.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a cone photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of opsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. Cone disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane during the development of the cone outer segment and remain contiguous with the ciliary membrane.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a rod photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of rhodopsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. It is thought that rod disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane near the base of the outer segment, which then become completely separated from the ciliary membrane, during the development of the rod outer segment.
The lipid bilayer that forms the outer-most layer of an organelle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments of the Golgi apparatus.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the vacuole and separating its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an autophagosome, a double-membrane-bounded vesicle in which endogenous cellular material is sequestered.
Any membrane that is part of an amphisome.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a vacuole that retains the same shape regardless of cell cycle phase. The membrane separates its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a protein storage vacuole.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the contractile vacuole.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a lytic vacuole and separating its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a vacuole, the shape of which correlates with cell cycle phase. The membrane separates its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell. An example of this structure is found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the lysosome and separating its contents from the cell cytoplasm.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an azurophil granule, a primary lysosomal granule found in neutrophil granulocytes that contains a wide range of hydrolytic enzymes and is released into the extracellular fluid.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endolysosome. An endolysosome is a transient hybrid organelle formed by fusion of a late endosome with a lysosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a phagolysosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the cytolytic granule.
A lipid bilayer that surrounds an autolysosome, a single-membrane-bounded vesicle in which endogenous cellular material is degraded.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a late endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a multivesicular body.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endolysosome. An endolysosome is a transient hybrid organelle formed by fusion of a late endosome with a lysosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a recycling endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic recycling endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a presynaptic endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a macropinosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a transport vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: ER to Golgi transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi.

StringWithMarkup.String: Golgi to ER transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the Golgi to the ER.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances within the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances between the trans-Golgi network and other parts of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted acetylcholine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted glutamate transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted monoamine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an exocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a synaptic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle associated with the Golgi apparatus.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances between the trans-Golgi network and other parts of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a COPI-coated vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: Golgi to ER transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the Golgi to the ER.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances within the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a chitosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a coated vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: ER to Golgi transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a COPI-coated vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: Golgi to ER transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances from the Golgi to the ER.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances within the Golgi.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a vesicle transporting substances between the trans-Golgi network and other parts of the cell.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted acetylcholine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted glutamate transport vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: clathrin-sculpted gamma-aminobutyric acid transport vesicle membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted gamma-aminobutyric acid transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted monoamine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-coated phagocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an early phagosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a phagolysosome.
A membrane that surrounds one or more bacteroids (such as nitrogen-fixing bacteroids within legume root nodule cells).
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, of the two lipid bilayers surrounding an organellar chromatophore.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a secretory granule.

The membrane that surrounds the acrosomal lumen. The acrosome is a special type of lysosome in the head of a spermatozoon that contains acid hydrolases and is concerned with the breakdown of the outer membrane of the ovum during fertilization.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the platelet dense granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the platelet alpha granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a dense core granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a neuronal dense core vesicle.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an azurophil granule, a primary lysosomal granule found in neutrophil granulocytes that contains a wide range of hydrolytic enzymes and is released into the extracellular fluid.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a specific granule, a granule with a membranous, tubular internal structure, found primarily in mature neutrophil cells. Most are released into the extracellular fluid. Specific granules contain lactoferrin, lysozyme, vitamin B12 binding protein and elastase.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a chromaffin granule, a specialized secretory vesicle found in the cells of adrenal glands and various other organs, which is concerned with the synthesis, storage, metabolism, and secretion of epinephrine and norepinephrine.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a zymogen granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a tertiary granule.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a lamellar body. A lamellar body is a membrane-bounded organelle, specialized for the storage and secretion of various substances (surfactant phospholipids, glycoproteins and acid phosphates) which are arranged in the form of tightly packed, concentric, membrane sheets or lamellae. Has some similar properties to, but is distinct from, a lysosome.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an alveolar lamellar body, a specialized secretory organelle found in type II pneumocytes and involved in the synthesis, secretion, and reutilization of pulmonary surfactant.

The lipid bilayer surrounding an epidermal lamellar body, a specialized secretory organelle found in keratinocytes and involved in the formation of an impermeable, lipid-containing membrane that serves as a water barrier and is required for correct skin barrier function.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a ficolin-1-rich granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a dense granule of the type found in apicomplexan parasites.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the smooth endoplasmic reticulum.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the platelet dense tubular network.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a microbody.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a peroxisome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a glycosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a glyoxysome.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing in a cellular organelle, lipid bilayer of an organelle envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the plastid envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chromoplast envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the cyanelle envelope.
The pigmented membrane of a chloroplast thylakoid. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an aleurone grain.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the sarcoplasmic reticulum.

The part of the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane that contains calcium release channels, is devoted to calcium release and is juxtaposed to transverse tubule membrane. The junctional sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane consists of the junctional region of the terminal cisterna membrane.

The part of the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane that contains calcium pumps and is devoted to calcium uptake. The free sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane consists of the longitudinal sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane and the non-junctional region of the terminal cisterna membrane.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an acidocalcisome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments that make up the cis-Golgi network.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an attachment organelle. This is a region of the cell membrane facing the environment - in mycoplasma, part of the mycolate outer membrane.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments of the endoplasmic reticulum (ER)-Golgi intermediate compartment system.
The lipid bilayer surrounding an esterosome. This membrane has characteristics of rough endoplasmic reticulum (RER) membranes.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a microneme.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a hydrogenosome.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a cilium.
That part of the plasma membrane found in the ciliary pocket (also called flagellar pocket).
The membrane surrounding the outer segment of a vertebrate photoreceptor.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a non-motile cilium.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a cone photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of opsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. Cone disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane during the development of the cone outer segment and remain contiguous with the ciliary membrane.
Any membrane that is part of a pigment granule.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a melanosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a multivesicular body internal vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the spine apparatus.
Any membrane that is part of an omegasome.
The membrane of the perinuclear endoplasmic reticulum, which is the portion of endoplasmic reticulum, the intracellular network of tubules and cisternae, that occurs near the nucleus.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a magnetosome.
A cellular membrane associated with the phagophore assembly site.
A membrane enriched in complexes formed of reaction centers, accessory pigments and electron carriers, in which photosynthetic reactions take place.
The pigmented membrane of any thylakoid.
The pigmented membrane of a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.
The lipid bilayer membrane of any thylakoid within a plastid.
The pigmented membrane of a chloroplast thylakoid. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The lipid bilayer membrane of any thylakoid within a cyanelle.
The membrane of prothylakoids, underdeveloped thylakoids found in etioplasts, lacking competent photosynthetic membranes.
The lipid bilayer membrane of any thylakoid within an organellar chromatophore.
The lipid bilayer associated with a plasma membrane-derived chromatophore; surrounds chromatophores that form complete vesicles.
The pigmented membrane of a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.
A double layer of lipid molecules that surrounds an ascus, a capsule containing the sexual spores in some fungi.

StringWithMarkup.String: nuclear outer membrane-endoplasmic reticulum membrane network

nodes.description: The continuous network of membranes encompassing the nuclear outer membrane and the endoplasmic reticulum membrane.

A single or double lipid bilayer with any of several different proteinaceous coats that can associate with membranes. Membrane coats include those formed by clathrin plus an adaptor complex, the COPI and COPII complexes.
The region of the prospore membrane that extends to surround the spore nucleus; coated with specific proteins that are thought to play a role in prospore membrane organization.
A membrane that is a (regional) part of the plasma membrane.

The region of the plasma membrane located at the basal end of the cell. Often used in reference to animal polarized epithelial membranes, where the basal membrane is the part attached to the extracellular matrix, or in plant cells, where the basal membrane is defined with respect to the zygotic axis.

The region of the plasma membrane that includes the basal end and sides of the cell. Often used in reference to animal polarized epithelial membranes, where the basal membrane is the part attached to the extracellular matrix, or in plant cells, where the basal membrane is defined with respect to the zygotic axis.
The region of the plasma membrane located at the apical end of the cell.
The apical end of the lateral plasma membrane of epithelial cells.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a plasma membrane bounded cell surface projection.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a lamellipodium.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a uropod.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a pseudopodium.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding the brush border.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a filopodium.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a microvillus.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a microvillus of a rhabdomere.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a ruffle.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a neuron projection.

The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding an axon; it is a specialized trilaminar random mosaic of protein molecules floating within a fluid matrix of highly mobile phospholipid molecules, 7-8 nm in thickness.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendrite.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendritic spine.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a stereocilium.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding the rhabdomere.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a muscle cell projection.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a cilium.
That part of the plasma membrane found in the ciliary pocket (also called flagellar pocket).
The membrane surrounding the outer segment of a vertebrate photoreceptor.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a non-motile cilium.

Stack of disc membranes located inside a cone photoreceptor outer segment, and containing densely packed molecules of opsin photoreceptor proteins that traverse the lipid bilayer. Cone disc membranes arise as evaginations of the ciliary membrane during the development of the cone outer segment and remain contiguous with the ciliary membrane.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a mating projection, the projection formed by unicellular fungi in response to mating pheromone.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a macropinocytic cup.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding the cell tip.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a mating projection tip.

StringWithMarkup.String: plasma membrane of growing cell tip

nodes.description: Any plasma membrane part that is part of a growing cell tip.
The pigmented membrane of a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.
The cleavage furrow is a plasma membrane invagination at the cell division site. The cleavage furrow begins as a shallow groove and eventually deepens to divide the cytoplasm.
A membrane raft that is part of the plasma membrane.

A membrane raft that forms small pit, depression, or invagination that communicates with the outside of a cell and extends inward, indenting the cytoplasm and the cell membrane. Examples include flask-shaped invaginations of the plasma membrane in adipocytes associated with caveolin proteins, and minute pits or incuppings of the cell membrane formed during pinocytosis. Caveolae may be pinched off to form free vesicles within the cytoplasm.
A plasma membrane part that is composed of a furrow-like plasma membrane domain and associated integral transmembrane proteins.

The membrane surrounding the inner segment of a vertebrate photoreceptor. The photoreceptor inner segment contains mitochondria, ribosomes and membranes where opsin molecules are assembled and passed to be part of the outer segment discs.
A specialized area of membrane on either the presynaptic or the postsynaptic side of a synapse, the junction between a nerve fiber of one neuron and another neuron or muscle fiber or glial cell.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendritic spine.
A region that surrounds the active zone of the presynaptic plasma membrane, and is specialized for the control of synaptic development.

A specialized area of membrane of the axon terminal that faces the plasma membrane of the neuron or muscle fiber with which the axon terminal establishes a synaptic junction; many synaptic junctions exhibit structural presynaptic characteristics, such as conical, electron-dense internal protrusions, that distinguish it from the remainder of the axon plasma membrane.

A specialized area of membrane facing the presynaptic membrane on the tip of the nerve ending and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft). Neurotransmitters cross the synaptic cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane.
The membrane portion of the presynaptic active zone; it is the site where docking and fusion of synaptic vesicles occurs for the release of neurotransmitters.
The region of the presynaptic membrane that is part of the presynaptic endocytic zone - where synaptic vesicles are endocytosed and recycled following release.
The region of the postsynaptic membrane that is part of the postsynaptic endocytic zone. This region of membrane is associated with stable clathrin puncta.

The membrane component of the postsynaptic specialization. This is the region of the postsynaptic membrane in which the population of neurotransmitter receptors involved in synaptic transmission are concentrated.

The membrane component of the postsynaptic density. This is the region of the postsynaptic membrane in which the population of neurotransmitter receptors involved in synaptic transmission are concentrated.

StringWithMarkup.String: postsynaptic specialization membrane of symmetric synapse

nodes.description: The membrane component of the postsynaptic specialization of a symmetric synapse. This is the region of the postsynaptic membrane in which the population of neurotransmitter receptors involved in synaptic transmission are concentrated.

A membrane microdomain that forms a necklace around the bulb (crater) of a caveola. Intramembrane particles are concentrated in this region and cytoskeletal components, including actin, are highly enriched in the area underlying it.
A plasma membrane invagination at the site of separation of a multi-nucleate cell or syncytium into individual cells.

A scallop-shaped plaque, also referred to as an asymmetric unit membrane (AUM), found in the apical plasma membrane of urothelial superficial (umbrella) cells which form a a barrier to the passage of water and soluble toxic compounds found in urine. The plaques are thickened regions of membrane composed of uroplakin transmembrane proteins which form a crystalline array.

StringWithMarkup.String: hinge region between urothelial plaques of apical plasma membrane

nodes.description: A narrow rim of non-thickened membrane in between urothelial plaques in apical plasma membrane.

A plasma membrane region adjacent to the base of eukaryotic cilia and flagella that is enriched in endocytosis-associated proteins and vesicles and that appears to regulate ciliary membrane homeostasis.
The plasma membrane that is part of the head section of a sperm cell.

The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding the pellicle, a structure enclosing some parasite cells such as certain apicomplexa and Euglenozoa. These membranes are associated with an infrastructure of microtubules, microfilaments, and other organelles.
A membrane region with a lipid composition that is distinct from that of the membrane regions that surround it.

Any of the small (10-200 nm), heterogeneous, highly dynamic, sterol- and sphingolipid-enriched membrane domains that compartmentalize cellular processes. Small rafts can sometimes be stabilized to form larger platforms through protein-protein and protein-lipid interactions.
A membrane raft that is part of the plasma membrane.

A membrane raft that forms small pit, depression, or invagination that communicates with the outside of a cell and extends inward, indenting the cytoplasm and the cell membrane. Examples include flask-shaped invaginations of the plasma membrane in adipocytes associated with caveolin proteins, and minute pits or incuppings of the cell membrane formed during pinocytosis. Caveolae may be pinched off to form free vesicles within the cytoplasm.
A plasma membrane part that is composed of a furrow-like plasma membrane domain and associated integral transmembrane proteins.

A membrane microdomain that forms a necklace around the bulb (crater) of a caveola. Intramembrane particles are concentrated in this region and cytoskeletal components, including actin, are highly enriched in the area underlying it.
The region of a caveola that extends into the cytoplasm, excluding the neck (rim). This region is associated with intracellular caveola proteins.
Host-derived membrane of a pathogen-containing vacuole.
The membrane surrounding the spore core (endospore core) that separates it from its external environment.
The portion of the plasma membrane at the lateral side of the cell. In epithelial cells, lateral plasma membranes are on the sides of cells which lie at the interface of adjacent cells.

A dynamic, proteinaceous framework within the nucleus of eukaryotic cells, composed of proteins and RNA, that provides structural support for chromatin organization, gene regulation, and nuclear processes.
Extra-nucleolar nuclear domains usually visualized by confocal microscopy and fluorescent antibodies to specific proteins.

A small round nuclear body, measuring 0.2-0.8 microns in diameter that is diffusely distributed throughout the nucleoplasm. Several proteins known to be involved in miRNA processing have been localized to these structures. D-bodies are thought to be involved in primary-miRNA processing and/or storage/assembly of miRNA processing complexes.

A class of nuclear body, first seen after silver staining by Ramon y Cajal in 1903, enriched in small nuclear ribonucleoproteins, and certain general RNA polymerase II transcription factors; ultrastructurally, they appear as a tangle of coiled, electron-dense threads roughly 0.5 micrometers in diameter; involved in aspects of snRNP biogenesis; the protein coilin serves as a marker for Cajal bodies. Some argue that Cajal bodies are the sites for preassembly of transcriptosomes, unitary particles involved in transcription and processing of RNA.

A class of nuclear body; they react against SP100 auto-antibodies (PML, promyelocytic leukemia); cells typically contain 10-30 PML bodies per nucleus; alterations in the localization of PML bodies occurs after viral infection.

A nuclear body that is enriched in the lymphoid cell-specific protein LYSp100B; LANDs are globular, electron-dense structures and are morphologically distinct from the annular structures characteristic of PML bodies.
A discrete extra-nucleolar subnuclear domain, 20-50 in number, in which splicing factors are seen to be localized by immunofluorescence microscopy.

A nucleoplasmic speckle distributed in the interchromatin space of cells in close proximity to chromatin. Omega speckles are distinct from interchromatin granules and contain heterogeneous nuclear RNA-binding proteins (hnRNPs).

A class of nuclear body measuring 20-25 nm in diameter and distributed throughout the interchromatin space, linked together by thin fibrils. They are believed to be storage centers for various snRNAs, snRNPs, serine/arginine-rich proteins and RNA polymerase II. A typical mammalian cell contains 25-50 clusters of interchromatin granules. Interchromatin granule clusters do not contain the heterogeneous nuclear RNA-binding proteins (hnRNPs).

A nuclear body associated with the histone gene locus that is thought to contain all of the factors necessary for histone mRNA transcription and pre-mRNA processing. In Drosophila, U7 snRNP is located in the histone locus body rather than the distinct Cajal body.
Discrete subnuclear bodies in the interchromatin nucleoplasmic space, often located adjacent to nuclear specks. 10-20 paraspeckles are typically found in human cell nuclei.

A nuclear body that is found in the germinal vesicles of amphibian oocytes, and consist of three major parts: a remarkably spherical body about 5-10 pm in diameter, smaller spherical or nearly spherical granules on the surface, and inclusions of various sizes that strongly resemble the surface granules. The parts of the sphere organelle have distinct compositions, including splicing snRNAs and proteins.

A nuclear body that contains proteins involved in pre-mRNA 3'-end cleavage and polyadenylation, such as DDX1, CSTF2 and CPSFs, as well as the transcription factors TFIIE and TFIIF. Cleavage bodies are localized adjacent to Cajal bodies and are involved in mRNA3'-end processing.

Nuclear bodies frequently found near or associated with Cajal bodies (also called coiled bodies or CBs). Gemini of coiled bodies, or 'gems', are similar in size and shape to CBs, and often indistinguishable under the microscope. Unlike CBs, gems do not contain small nuclear ribonucleoproteins (snRNPs); they contain a protein called survivor of motor neurons (SMN) whose function relates to snRNP biogenesis. Gems are believed to assist CBs in snRNP biogenesis, and to play a role in the etiology of spinal muscular atrophy (SMA).
An nuclear body involved in nuclear mRNA surveilllance. Contains at least Mmi1, or an ortholog of it, and the nuclear exosome.

Any cellular component of a host cell. The host is an organism in which another organism, for instance a parasite or symbiont, spends part or all of its life cycle and from which it obtains nourishment and/or protection.
Any constituent part of a host cell. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The space between a symbiont plasma membrane and the symbiont-containing vacuole membrane.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a symbiont-containing vacuole, derived from both the host and symbiont.
Tubular network of extensions from the symbiont-containing vacuole membrane that protrude into the host cytoplasm.

Double layer of lipid molecules as it encloses host cells, and, in eukaryotes, many organelles; may be a single or double lipid bilayer; also includes associated proteins. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The plasma membrane surrounding a host cell.

A collection of membranous structures involved in transport within the host cell. The main components of the endomembrane system are endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi bodies, vesicles, cell membrane and nuclear envelope. Members of the endomembrane system pass materials through each other or though the use of vesicles. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The pigmented membrane of any host thylakoid.

Any sac-like membranous structures (cisternae) in a chloroplast found in host cells, combined into stacks (grana) and present singly in the stroma (stroma thylakoids or frets) as interconnections between grana. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell cytoplasmic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host synaptic vesicle.

StringWithMarkup.String: double membrane vesicle viral factory membrane

nodes.description: One of the two endoplasmic reticulum-derived lipid bilayer membranes that bound a double membrane vesicle viral factory.

StringWithMarkup.String: double membrane vesicle viral factory inner membrane

nodes.description: The inner of the two endoplasmic reticulum-derived lipid bilayer membranes that bound a double membrane vesicle viral factory.

StringWithMarkup.String: double membrane vesicle viral factory outer membrane

nodes.description: The outer of the two endoplasmic reticulum-derived lipid bilayer membranes that bound a double membrane vesicle viral factory.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the host cell endoplasmic reticulum.

StringWithMarkup.String: host cell rough endoplasmic reticulum membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding the host cell rough endoplasmic reticulum.

StringWithMarkup.String: host cell smooth endoplasmic reticulum membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding the host cell smooth endoplasmic reticulum.

StringWithMarkup.String: host cell endoplasmic reticulum-Golgi intermediate compartment membrane

nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments of the host cell ER-Golgi intermediate compartment system.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell late endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments of the host cell Golgi apparatus.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the host cell lysosome and separating its contents from the host cell cytoplasm.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the host cell mitochondrion and form the host cell mitochondrial envelope.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the host cell mitochondrial envelope. It is highly folded to form cristae.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the host cell mitochondrial envelope.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the host nucleus and form the nuclear envelope; excludes the intermembrane space.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the host nuclear envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the host nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the host cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes.
The external membrane of Gram-negative bacteria or certain organelles such as mitochondria and chloroplasts; freely permeable to most ions and metabolites, occurring in a host cell.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing in a cellular organelle, lipid bilayer of an organelle envelope, occurring in a host cell.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the host cell mitochondrial envelope.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the host nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the host cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes.
A lipid bilayer that forms the outermost layer of the cell envelope, occurring in a host cell.
The membrane surrounding the symbiont haustorium during symbiosis, derived from the host plasma membrane.
A host-derived membrane surrounding the symbiont hypha during infection.
A host-derived membrane surrounding the symbiont arbuscule during symbiosis.

Any constituent part of the living contents of a host cell; the matter contained within (but not including) the plasma membrane, usually taken to exclude large vacuoles and masses of secretory or ingested material. In eukaryotes it includes the nucleus and cytoplasm. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The cytoplasm of a host cell.

Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function, occurring within the host cell. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, vesicles, ribosomes and the cytoskeleton. Excludes the plasma membrane. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function, as found in host cells, bounded by a single or double lipid bilayer membrane and occurring within the cell. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, and vesicles. Excludes the plasma membrane. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

A semiautonomous, self replicating organelle as found in host cells that occurs in varying numbers, shapes, and sizes in the cell cytoplasm. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

Any member of a family of organelles as found in the cytoplasm of host cells, which are membrane-bounded and contain DNA. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

A chlorophyll-containing plastid as found within host cells with thylakoids organized into grana and frets, or stroma thylakoids, and embedded in a stroma. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

Any constituent part of a chloroplast as it is found in host cells and which are a chlorophyll-containing plastid with thylakoids organized into grana and frets, or stroma thylakoids, and embedded in a stroma. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

Any sac-like membranous structures (cisternae) in a chloroplast found in host cells, combined into stacks (grana) and present singly in the stroma (stroma thylakoids or frets) as interconnections between grana. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
A membrane-bounded organelle as it is found in the host cell in which chromosomes are housed and replicated. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
A double-enveloped cell compartment, composed of the endosymbiont with its plasmalemma (as inner envelope) and an outer envelope (the perisymbiontic membrane) derived from the host cell.
A symbiosome containing any of various structurally modified bacteria, such as those occurring on the root nodules of leguminous plants, of a host cell.
A vesicle formed of membrane or protein, found in the cytoplasm of a host cell.

A secretory organelle of a host cell, some 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals; accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.

The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host ER takes two forms, rough (or granular), with ribosomes adhering to the outer surface, and smooth (with no ribosomes attached).

The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host rough ER has ribosomes adhering to the outer surface.

The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host smooth ER has no ribosomes adhering to the outer surface.

StringWithMarkup.String: host cell endoplasmic reticulum-Golgi intermediate compartment

nodes.description: A complex system of membrane-bounded compartments located between host cell endoplasmic reticulum (ER) and the host Golgi complex, with a distinctive membrane protein composition; involved in ER-to-Golgi transport.
A membrane-bounded organelle that carries materials newly ingested by endocytosis. It passes many of the materials to host cell lysosomes for degradation.

A prelysosomal endocytic organelle differentiated from host early endosomes by lower lumenal pH and different protein composition. Host late endosomes are more spherical than early endosomes and are mostly juxtanuclear, being concentrated near the microtubule organizing center.

A late endosome in which regions of the limiting host cell endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; host membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the host cytoplasm.

A small lytic vacuole that has cell cycle-independent morphology and is found in most host animal cells and that contains a variety of hydrolases, most of which have their maximal activities in the pH range 5-6. The contained enzymes display latency if properly isolated. About 40 different lysosomal hydrolases are known and host cell lysosomes have a great variety of morphologies and functions.
A membrane-bounded compartment that forms in the cytoplasm of the host cell, in which virus assembly takes place.

A small host cell organelle enclosed by a single membrane, and found in most eukaryotic cells. Contains peroxidases and other enzymes involved in a variety of metabolic processes including free radical detoxification, lipid catabolism and biosynthesis, and hydrogen peroxide metabolism.

A membranous cellular structure within the host cell that bears the photosynthetic pigments in plants, algae, and cyanobacteria. In cyanobacteria thylakoids are of various shapes and are attached to, or continuous with, the host plasma membrane. In eukaryotic host cells they are flattened, membrane-bounded disk-like structures located in the chloroplasts; in the chloroplasts of higher plants the thylakoids form dense stacks called grana. Isolated thylakoid preparations can carry out photosynthetic electron transport and the associated phosphorylation.

A cellular structure that forms the internal framework of eukaryotic and prokaryotic host cells. The cytoskeleton includes intermediate filaments, microfilaments, microtubules, the microtrabecular lattice, and other structures characterized by a polymeric filamentous nature and long-range order within the cell. The various elements of the cytoskeleton not only serve in the maintenance of cellular shape but also have roles in other cellular functions, including cellular movement, cell division, endocytosis, and movement of organelles.

A structure in a host cell comprised of a core structure (in most organisms, a pair of centrioles) and peripheral material from which a microtubule-based structure, such as a spindle apparatus, is organized. Centrosomes occur close to the nucleus during interphase in many eukaryotic cells, though in animal cells it changes continually during the cell-division cycle.
A structure composed of a very long molecule of DNA and associated proteins (e.g. histones) that carries hereditary information, occurring within a host cell.

Any constituent part of the host cell cytoplasm, all of the contents of a cell excluding the plasma membrane and nucleus, but including other subcellular structures. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
Membrane-bounded vacuole within a host cell in which a symbiont organism resides. The vacuole membrane is derived from both the host and symbiont.
Protrusion that develops in the plasma membrane of a parasitized erythrocyte. An example of this component is found in Plasmodium species.

A disk-like structure that appears at the periphery of a red blood cell infected by an apicomplexan parasite, characterized by a translucent lumen and an electron-dense coat of variable thickness; often appears to be tethered to the host cell membrane by fibrous connections with the erythrocyte cytoskeleton.

A semiautonomous, self replicating organelle as found in host cells that occurs in varying numbers, shapes, and sizes in the cell cytoplasm. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
A viral factory located in the cytoplasm of a host cell.

A cytoplasmic viral factory that is electron dense due to high levels of viral RNA. Produced by nucleo-cytoplasmic large DNA viruses (NCLDV) like Poxviridae, Asfarviridae and Iridoviridae, and dsRNA viruses like Reoviridae.
A cytoplasmic viral factory which is a 50-400nm diameter membrane invagination. Spherules can appear on several enveloped cellular components depending on the virus.

A cytoplasmic viral factory that consists of a double-membrane bound vesicle. Has a diameter of 200-300nm and is derived from the endoplasmic reticulum or Golgi apparatus. Produced by Picornaviridae, Nidovirales, Arteriviridae and Coronaviridae.

A cytoplasmic viral factory derived from the Golgi in which Bunyaviridae replication takes place. Tubes are membranous structures close to the assembly and budding sites, and their function may be to connect viral replication and morphogenesis inside viral factories.
A membrane-bounded compartment that forms in the cytoplasm of the host cell, in which virus assembly takes place.
A double-enveloped cell compartment, composed of the endosymbiont with its plasmalemma (as inner envelope) and an outer envelope (the perisymbiontic membrane) derived from the host cell.
A symbiosome containing any of various structurally modified bacteria, such as those occurring on the root nodules of leguminous plants, of a host cell.
The pigmented membrane of any host thylakoid.

Any sac-like membranous structures (cisternae) in a chloroplast found in host cells, combined into stacks (grana) and present singly in the stroma (stroma thylakoids or frets) as interconnections between grana. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
A vesicle formed of membrane or protein, found in the cytoplasm of a host cell.

A secretory organelle of a host cell, some 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals; accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell cytoplasmic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell endocytic vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a host synaptic vesicle.

The part of the host cell cytoplasm that does not contain organelles but which does contain other particulate matter, such as protein complexes.

The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host ER takes two forms, rough (or granular), with ribosomes adhering to the outer surface, and smooth (with no ribosomes attached).

The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host rough ER has ribosomes adhering to the outer surface.

A prelysosomal endocytic organelle differentiated from host early endosomes by lower lumenal pH and different protein composition. Host late endosomes are more spherical than early endosomes and are mostly juxtanuclear, being concentrated near the microtubule organizing center.

A late endosome in which regions of the limiting host cell endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; host membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the host cytoplasm.
A compound membranous cytoplasmic organelle of eukaryotic host cells, consisting of flattened, ribosome-free vesicles arranged in a more or less regular stack.
Any particle of coalesced lipids in the cytoplasm of a host cell. May include associated proteins.

A small lytic vacuole that has cell cycle-independent morphology and is found in most host animal cells and that contains a variety of hydrolases, most of which have their maximal activities in the pH range 5-6. The contained enzymes display latency if properly isolated. About 40 different lysosomal hydrolases are known and host cell lysosomes have a great variety of morphologies and functions.
The double lipid bilayer enclosing the host cell mitochondrion and separating its contents from the host cell cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.description: The host cell cytoplasm situated near, or occurring around, the host nucleus.
The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the host cell mitochondrial envelope.
The volume enclosed by the membranes of the host cell endosome.
A complex, symbiont-induced host-derived organelle that is comprised of multiple protein and lipid domains.

A small host cell organelle enclosed by a single membrane, and found in most eukaryotic cells. Contains peroxidases and other enzymes involved in a variety of metabolic processes including free radical detoxification, lipid catabolism and biosynthesis, and hydrogen peroxide metabolism.
